And now, then, we may go on to speak of one office of photography‚ which exalts it to the dignity of an assistant to genius and taste—as the faithful servant of genius, as the convenient ally of taste. It is not in representing living nature in her fit· fulness of feature—to this it is not equal—but in copying for us the completed works of great painters, and sculptors, and architects in their ex- actness (saving colour in the case of painting),— in presenting us with a delineation more accurate, and so fitter for the purposes of study, than any other, that its peculiar value lies.
